1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,120
 Well, welcome to The Vine.

2
00:00:01,120 --> 00:00:06,640
 If you're new, we're so glad that you're with us here this morning.

3
00:00:06,640 --> 00:00:11,880
 If you are back with us for the first Sunday of 2026, maybe you were traveling last week,

4
00:00:11,880 --> 00:00:13,880
 but you're back here this Sunday.

5
00:00:13,880 --> 00:00:16,000
 We're so glad that you're back with us.

6
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:22,800
 Last week, I started the year by explaining a little bit around the season that we feel

7
00:00:22,800 --> 00:00:26,560
 like as a leadership here at The Vine, that we feel God wants us and the focus really

8
00:00:26,560 --> 00:00:29,160
 that he wants us to start this new year with.

9
00:00:29,160 --> 00:00:34,560
 And that is by teaching into the context of seasons of waiting.

10
00:00:34,560 --> 00:00:39,040
 And so much of the songs that we were singing here this morning and the devotions, if you've

11
00:00:39,040 --> 00:00:44,440
 been listening to them throughout the week, this week, we're really leaning into the reality

12
00:00:44,440 --> 00:00:50,440
 that for many of us here, we're either currently in a season of waiting or we are about to

13
00:00:50,440 --> 00:00:52,980
 go into a season of waiting.

14
00:00:52,980 --> 00:00:57,200
 Some of us have perhaps been in those seasons of waiting for a long period of time.

15
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:01,200
 And as a leadership, as we were praying about the start of this year, we felt like the Lord

16
00:01:01,200 --> 00:01:05,120
 is saying, "I want to minister to people in the place of waiting.

17
00:01:05,120 --> 00:01:11,080
 And I want to particularly minister pastorally to them and compassionately and powerfully

18
00:01:11,080 --> 00:01:13,120
 renew their strength."

19
00:01:13,120 --> 00:01:17,280
 And so what we're going to be doing over this month of January as we're fasting together

20
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:21,280
 is we're going to be leaning into this idea of this place of waiting.

21
00:01:21,280 --> 00:01:25,520
 And we explained last week that we human beings, we don't like to wait.

22
00:01:25,520 --> 00:01:29,880
 But in our modern context, in the world in which we're living in right now, we really

23
00:01:29,880 --> 00:01:30,880
 don't like waiting.

24
00:01:30,880 --> 00:01:38,080
 In fact, we've come to see waiting in the modern perspective as failure or as punishment.

25
00:01:38,080 --> 00:01:42,200
 Like if we can't get something and get it quickly, once we've ordered our coffee, we

26
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:43,760
 wanted to come fast.

27
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:47,560
 Once we've purchased something, we want to be able to get hold of it straight away.

28
00:01:47,560 --> 00:01:55,480
 As human beings, we place in our modern context a really high value on receiving things quickly.

29
00:01:55,480 --> 00:01:59,600
 And the issue for us Christians, as we were talking about last week, is we've brought

30
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:01,800
 this into our Christianity.

31
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:03,840
 We brought this into our faith.

32
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:07,480
 And so we expect God to act and act immediately.

33
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:12,080
 That surely if God loves me, surely if God is the person of the scriptures, surely if

34
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:18,600
 his character and his nature is how we see it to be, then God should act and act immediately.

35
00:02:18,600 --> 00:02:23,000
 And when God doesn't act immediately, we want an upgrade.

36
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:24,720
 We struggle with it.

37
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:26,400
 And I think as Christians, here's what we do.

38
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:29,740
 We do one of two things or we do both of them.

39
00:02:29,740 --> 00:02:36,880
 We either begin to doubt God and begin to question his character or we doubt ourselves

40
00:02:36,880 --> 00:02:39,640
 and we question our character.

41
00:02:39,640 --> 00:02:41,120
 Or perhaps there's brokenness in me.

42
00:02:41,120 --> 00:02:42,580
 Perhaps there's too much sin in me.

43
00:02:42,580 --> 00:02:43,660
 Perhaps I haven't prayed enough.

44
00:02:43,660 --> 00:02:44,660
 Perhaps I haven't given enough.

45
00:02:44,660 --> 00:02:47,960
 Perhaps I haven't done or gone to church enough or whatever it is.

46
00:02:47,960 --> 00:02:53,040
 But we either begin to blame God or we blame ourselves when we as Christians don't receive

47
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:58,480
 from God what we think we should receive from him in the timeframe that we think he should

48
00:02:58,480 --> 00:03:00,720
 give it to us.

49
00:03:00,720 --> 00:03:07,580
 And we saw last week that there are over 200 scriptures in the Bible about seasons of waiting.

50
00:03:07,580 --> 00:03:12,640
 And if you do a survey of all of those scriptures, you'll come to see that when the Bible speaks

51
00:03:12,640 --> 00:03:20,040
 of seasons of waiting, it predominantly speaks about them as a gift, which is not how I feel

52
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:22,600
 about my seasons of waiting in my life.

53
00:03:22,600 --> 00:03:25,040
 But scripture says it's a gift.

54
00:03:25,040 --> 00:03:30,060
 It's a gift because you get to encounter something of God's character that's perhaps different

55
00:03:30,060 --> 00:03:32,080
 from what you've ever felt.

56
00:03:32,080 --> 00:03:35,800
 That you get to see something fresh about him.

57
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:40,320
 That in stripping away maybe some of that immediacy that we so often live off in our

58
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:47,560
 modern context, we begin to lean in more to a desperate desire to God to meet us.

59
00:03:47,560 --> 00:03:51,480
 I said last week that sometimes seasons of waiting are actually healthy for us.

60
00:03:51,480 --> 00:03:53,520
 They force us to slow down.

61
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:59,960
 They help us to strip away some of that ugly self-dependence that we can have upon ourselves.

62
00:03:59,960 --> 00:04:04,560
 It causes us to realize that we're actually not God.

63
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:10,720
 That we do need something outside of ourselves to meet us and strengthen us and help us and

64
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:12,760
 guide us through life.

65
00:04:12,760 --> 00:04:15,440
 Seasons of waiting are a gift.

66
00:04:15,440 --> 00:04:19,160
 And we said last week that one of the most beautiful ways that you see that is through

67
00:04:19,160 --> 00:04:20,160
 Psalm 27.

68
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:24,800
 And Psalm 27 is the Psalm that we're going to be sitting in over the next four weeks

69
00:04:24,800 --> 00:04:27,600
 as we unpack this beautiful Psalm of King David.

70
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:31,760
 And I showed us last week that right at the end of the Psalm, he says, "Wait for the Lord."

71
00:04:31,760 --> 00:04:36,360
 He says, "Take heart and have strength and wait for the Lord."

72
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:39,520
 And interestingly, the word "wait" there, as we talked about last week, is the word

73
00:04:39,520 --> 00:04:41,000
 "kavah" in Hebrew.

74
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:49,320
 It literally means this, to gather together, to bind together, and to look and to expect.

75
00:04:49,320 --> 00:04:54,080
 Which is really different from how we often think about seasons of waiting.

76
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:59,800
 That in the Hebrew mindset, a waiting is to gather together all of your hope, all of the

77
00:04:59,800 --> 00:05:06,560
 facts, all of the stuff that's happening in life, and look and expect and have a expectancy

78
00:05:06,560 --> 00:05:10,700
 within you that God is about to do something.

79
00:05:10,700 --> 00:05:13,920
 But in our modern context and how we often think about waiting, we think about waiting

80
00:05:13,920 --> 00:05:16,040
 as inactivity.

81
00:05:16,040 --> 00:05:19,320
 That waiting is like this place of like, "Oh, I'm in a waiting.

82
00:05:19,320 --> 00:05:20,880
 I can't do anything.

83
00:05:20,880 --> 00:05:22,800
 I have to wait."

84
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:25,380
 That's not how the Hebrews thought of it.

85
00:05:25,380 --> 00:05:29,360
 They thought about waiting not as this like, "Oh my gosh, I can't do anything."

86
00:05:29,360 --> 00:05:35,360
 They thought about waiting as like, "I am expecting that God is going to act.

87
00:05:35,360 --> 00:05:36,920
 He hasn't acted yet.

88
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:41,200
 I'm waiting, but I'm expecting that He will do so."

89
00:05:41,200 --> 00:05:47,160
 So in Hebrew thinking, waiting is not inactivity or it's not idleness.

90
00:05:47,160 --> 00:05:51,520
 It's active anticipation of change.

91
00:05:51,520 --> 00:05:53,120
 Think about that for a sec.

92
00:05:53,120 --> 00:05:57,760
 That waiting is active anticipation of change.

93
00:05:57,760 --> 00:06:01,800
 And oh yes, I would love that change to happen today.

94
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:04,200
 I would love for my prayers to be answered straight away.

95
00:06:04,200 --> 00:06:08,120
 I would love for that healing that I'm looking for to come into my life immediately.

96
00:06:08,120 --> 00:06:14,120
 But when I wait, as I'm waiting on the Lord to respond to those prayers and do what only

97
00:06:14,120 --> 00:06:20,560
 He can do, I have within me an active anticipation that change is coming.

98
00:06:20,560 --> 00:06:21,880
 Come on church.

99
00:06:21,880 --> 00:06:30,120
 I'm not sitting around idly, inactive, or wallowing in my own self-pity and denial.

100
00:06:30,120 --> 00:06:33,600
 Waiting in the Bible is a prophetic act.

101
00:06:33,600 --> 00:06:42,640
 It is God's people leaning forward in excitement and anticipation, not disregarding the reality

102
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:50,200
 that waiting is hard, not ignoring some of the emotions that come alongside of longer

103
00:06:50,200 --> 00:06:57,280
 periods of waiting, but believing that Yahweh is active.

104
00:06:57,280 --> 00:07:04,480
 And if He's active, then I stand on an active anticipation within myself that God is going

105
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:05,680
 to come through.

106
00:07:05,680 --> 00:07:14,120
 I hope it's today, but if it's not, I will lean in to the season of waiting with faith.

107
00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:16,320
 That's very good news, isn't it?

108
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:17,320
 No?

109
00:07:17,320 --> 00:07:20,080
 Is that very good news?

110
00:07:20,080 --> 00:07:24,760
 It's very good news, but it's not always comforting news.

111
00:07:24,760 --> 00:07:28,240
 It's not always comforting news because I don't know about you, but when I go through

112
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:33,520
 my seasons of waiting, I'm in one right now, as I'm going through seasons of waiting myself,

113
00:07:33,520 --> 00:07:35,200
 it's hard.

114
00:07:35,200 --> 00:07:37,400
 It's painful.

115
00:07:37,400 --> 00:07:39,520
 It's challenging.

116
00:07:39,520 --> 00:07:41,880
 It's difficult.

117
00:07:41,880 --> 00:07:45,480
 And so what David does in Psalm 27 is something quite beautiful.

118
00:07:45,480 --> 00:07:50,720
 Psalm 27 is broken down, it's a poem, and it's broken into four stanzas.

119
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:55,440
 In each of the stanzas, particularly when you see it in the Hebrew, David provides a

120
00:07:55,440 --> 00:07:59,800
 negative aspect of waiting, which is great because that connects with all of us, but

121
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:02,400
 then he shows his antidote to it.

122
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:07,880
 He teaches us that, yeah, there are these four negative things that happen when we wait,

123
00:08:07,880 --> 00:08:13,080
 but yet here's the way in which we can encounter those things and turn them around so that

124
00:08:13,080 --> 00:08:19,140
 our waiting is an anticipation of change and not a wallowing in self-pity and denial.

125
00:08:19,140 --> 00:08:23,360
 And so over the next four weeks, we're going to step through each of these different stanzas

126
00:08:23,360 --> 00:08:27,160
 of the poem, and we're going to draw out for you what the negative thing is, but then we're

127
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:31,520
 going to show you what David's antidote to that is, and I believe that this is going

128
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:36,200
 to be super important and helpful for any of you in seasons of waiting.

129
00:08:36,200 --> 00:08:39,600
 And today we're just going to look at the first stanza, the first three verses of Psalm

130
00:08:39,600 --> 00:08:40,600
 27.

131
00:08:40,600 --> 00:08:42,320
 Is everybody okay?

132
00:08:42,320 --> 00:08:44,400
 Let me read this to you.

133
00:08:44,400 --> 00:08:47,320
 The Lord is my light and my salvation.

134
00:08:47,320 --> 00:08:49,880
 Whom shall I fear?

135
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:51,720
 The Lord is the stronghold of my life.

136
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,580
 Of whom shall I be afraid?

137
00:08:54,580 --> 00:08:59,640
 When evil doers came upon me to devour my flesh, my adversaries and my enemies, they

138
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:02,420
 stumbled and fell.

139
00:09:02,420 --> 00:09:05,480
 If an army encamps against me, my heart will not fear.

140
00:09:05,480 --> 00:09:12,560
 If war rises up against me, in spite of this, I am confident.

141
00:09:12,560 --> 00:09:19,000
 There's this phenomena in Bible study and scripture reading that sometimes interpretation

142
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:23,220
 of a passage actually goes in the opposite direction to what you think.

143
00:09:23,220 --> 00:09:28,840
 Sometimes the end of a passage helps you to better understand the start of the passage.

144
00:09:28,840 --> 00:09:34,280
 This happens a lot in poetic words within scripture, that often in a poetic form of

145
00:09:34,280 --> 00:09:40,160
 Hebrew there's parallelisms and symbolisms, and sometimes you need to get to the last

146
00:09:40,160 --> 00:09:44,440
 part of the thought to really understand the first part that was given.

147
00:09:44,440 --> 00:09:47,880
 Interestingly, this is also seen in the New Testament.

148
00:09:47,880 --> 00:09:53,080
 The apostle Paul was a beautiful writer, and there's a number of passages in Paul where

149
00:09:53,080 --> 00:09:56,560
 actually you have to read through the whole passage and kind of get to the end of the

150
00:09:56,560 --> 00:10:01,560
 passage before you can fully begin to really understand what is happening at the start.

151
00:10:01,560 --> 00:10:04,520
 And I think David is doing something here in this.

152
00:10:04,520 --> 00:10:10,280
 In fact, the end of these verses helps us to understand the fullness of the impact of

153
00:10:10,280 --> 00:10:11,280
 the first.

154
00:10:11,280 --> 00:10:15,040
 So what I want to do with you today is actually start in verse 3, and I want to work our way

155
00:10:15,040 --> 00:10:17,280
 back to verse 1.

156
00:10:17,280 --> 00:10:19,280
 He says this in verse 3.

157
00:10:19,280 --> 00:10:23,480
 If an army encamps against me, my heart will not fear.

158
00:10:23,480 --> 00:10:28,840
 If war arises against me, in spite of this, I am confident.

159
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:31,160
 I love what David does here.

160
00:10:31,160 --> 00:10:36,280
 Throughout the Psalm, there's imagery of war and there's imagery of battles, which makes

161
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:37,280
 sense.

162
00:10:37,280 --> 00:10:38,280
 This is King David.

163
00:10:38,280 --> 00:10:41,840
 He's experienced a lot of war and a lot of battles in his life, and so he's explaining

164
00:10:41,840 --> 00:10:42,840
 it.

165
00:10:42,840 --> 00:10:45,840
 But I want you to notice something really important about verse 3.

166
00:10:45,840 --> 00:10:50,760
 He's talking about the context of war, but interestingly, he's not talking about a battle

167
00:10:50,760 --> 00:10:52,680
 that is happening.

168
00:10:52,680 --> 00:10:57,160
 He's not saying, "I'm right now in this war," or, "This battle's happening."

169
00:10:57,160 --> 00:11:03,320
 He's saying this, "When an army encamps around me," he says, another way of reading the Hebrew

170
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:10,160
 in the second part, "If war arises against me or if rumor of war comes against me."

171
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:11,160
 He's talking about this.

172
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:14,680
 He's like, "You want to know when I'm really afraid?

173
00:11:14,680 --> 00:11:17,520
 You want to know when anxiety really builds in me?"

174
00:11:17,520 --> 00:11:20,120
 It's actually not in the fighting of the battle.

175
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:21,720
 It's not actually in the war itself.

176
00:11:21,720 --> 00:11:26,680
 When I get really anxious, when I get really afraid, it's when the army has encamped around

177
00:11:26,680 --> 00:11:30,080
 me, but they haven't attacked yet.

178
00:11:30,080 --> 00:11:35,120
 When I hear rumor of war, but the war hasn't happened yet, he's like, "That's when I feel

179
00:11:35,120 --> 00:11:36,120
 it."

180
00:11:36,120 --> 00:11:41,600
 In other words, it's in the waiting for the attack to come that I feel more fear than

181
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:44,280
 I actually do in the battle itself.

182
00:11:44,280 --> 00:11:47,680
 He's like, "You want to understand one of the things that's happening for all of us

183
00:11:47,680 --> 00:11:49,520
 in seasons of waiting."

184
00:11:49,520 --> 00:11:56,920
 See, in the waiting, and there is this anticipation within us of what's about to happen, that

185
00:11:56,920 --> 00:12:03,280
 is sometimes so much worse than the eventual reality of what actually takes place.

186
00:12:03,280 --> 00:12:06,000
 That's classic anxiety.

187
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:10,560
 But it's not actually in the eventual reality that is as worse as we thought it.

188
00:12:10,560 --> 00:12:13,840
 It's the wait that makes it feel a lot more worse.

189
00:12:13,840 --> 00:12:15,520
 Does that make sense?

190
00:12:15,520 --> 00:12:21,120
 So he's saying, "Here's where fear, here's where anxiety," which is the first of these

191
00:12:21,120 --> 00:12:24,840
 negative aspects of waiting, "Here's how it gets into us.

192
00:12:24,840 --> 00:12:32,460
 It gets into us because in the wait, we spiral in what we're thinking about the actual outcome

193
00:12:32,460 --> 00:12:35,000
 that will happen to us."

194
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:40,560
 You'll understand this if you've ever had a doctor say to you when you go in for a test

195
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:45,520
 something like, "Well, you've either grazed your knee or it's cancer."

196
00:12:45,520 --> 00:12:47,320
 Have you ever had a doctor say that to you?

197
00:12:47,320 --> 00:12:49,400
 Like it's either one extreme or the other, right?

198
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:53,080
 Like it's either something really easy or something not really good at all.

199
00:12:53,080 --> 00:12:55,740
 Oftentimes we might have this in cancer.

200
00:12:55,740 --> 00:12:58,560
 And then we're going to take some blood tests, and in a week's time, we're going to come

201
00:12:58,560 --> 00:13:00,480
 back to you and tell you the results.

202
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:04,880
 That week, I don't know about you, but that week is where the anxiety and fear comes to

203
00:13:04,880 --> 00:13:06,340
 me, right?

204
00:13:06,340 --> 00:13:09,600
 Not necessarily when the result comes back, but actually in the waiting of the result

205
00:13:09,600 --> 00:13:10,680
 because here's what happens.

206
00:13:10,680 --> 00:13:14,400
 We as human beings, we spiral in our thinking, and as we're waiting for the doctor to get

207
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:18,440
 back to us with the results of the blood test, we begin to think the worst case scenario

208
00:13:18,440 --> 00:13:20,880
 is going to happen.

209
00:13:20,880 --> 00:13:22,800
 Anyone connecting with this?

210
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:27,360
 Or perhaps there's a hard conversation you need to have with somebody at work, and you

211
00:13:27,360 --> 00:13:31,800
 aren't able to have that conversation for another week, but you begin to spiral thinking,

212
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:36,200
 "Man, their reaction is going to be far worse than I thought it was going to be."

213
00:13:36,200 --> 00:13:39,240
 And actually, in the end, when you have the conversation, their reaction is really not

214
00:13:39,240 --> 00:13:45,520
 that bad, but your thinking in the wait created it to be way worse than it was in the reality.

215
00:13:45,520 --> 00:13:46,520
 Following?

216
00:13:46,520 --> 00:13:51,520
 Or perhaps you're praying for a spouse, or you're asking for a new relationship in your

217
00:13:51,520 --> 00:13:55,520
 life, and the wait has gone on, and it's gone on, and it's gone on, and you're beginning

218
00:13:55,520 --> 00:14:01,920
 to feel this anxiety within you that you will never find that person, that you will never...

219
00:14:01,920 --> 00:14:07,820
 When the wait extends, the spiraling gets worse and worse and worse.

220
00:14:07,820 --> 00:14:10,600
 And David's saying to Israel, "You want to know when I feel fear?

221
00:14:10,600 --> 00:14:13,420
 It's not necessarily when the battle's happening.

222
00:14:13,420 --> 00:14:15,600
 It's before the battle.

223
00:14:15,600 --> 00:14:21,340
 When they've encamped around me, the night before the attack is far worse than the attack

224
00:14:21,340 --> 00:14:22,340
 itself."

225
00:14:22,340 --> 00:14:28,760
 One thing we have to understand is that before we fight a battle in the flesh, we have to

226
00:14:28,760 --> 00:14:33,240
 first fight the battle that's in our minds.

227
00:14:33,240 --> 00:14:36,440
 That's the first thing we have to realize in seasons of waiting, that actually the battle

228
00:14:36,440 --> 00:14:41,040
 that truly is going on, it's not necessarily the battle of the circumstances and situations

229
00:14:41,040 --> 00:14:42,920
 around us, as much as that might be.

230
00:14:42,920 --> 00:14:45,560
 It's the battle that is happening in our minds.

231
00:14:45,560 --> 00:14:47,000
 It's the way that we think.

232
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:49,080
 It's the spiraling that is happening.

233
00:14:49,080 --> 00:14:52,720
 As the wait increases, the negativity takes root.

234
00:14:52,720 --> 00:14:57,880
 The battle that you really need to fight is, first of all, in your mind.

235
00:14:57,880 --> 00:15:01,480
 And David's saying, "That's where I've found it really hard.

236
00:15:01,480 --> 00:15:07,000
 That's why seasons of waiting are really challenging, because I know what it is to feel that anxiety

237
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:08,240
 building within me."

238
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:15,600
 He says to his people, "It's on the eve of battle where we have to really do the fighting

239
00:15:15,600 --> 00:15:18,080
 in the battle of our minds."

240
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:22,760
 Some of you here, that really resonates with you, because I think you really know personally

241
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:27,080
 what that mental and emotional battle is like.

242
00:15:27,080 --> 00:15:31,400
 You understand that challenge that there is in seasons of waiting when we begin to think

243
00:15:31,400 --> 00:15:38,040
 things are way worse than perhaps they will ever end up actually being when the time finally

244
00:15:38,040 --> 00:15:40,560
 comes.

245
00:15:40,560 --> 00:15:47,280
 And David, in introducing to us this anxiety of waiting, offers two solutions to it.

246
00:15:47,280 --> 00:15:50,080
 So this is resonating with you, and you're thinking to yourself, "I have this battle

247
00:15:50,080 --> 00:15:51,080
 in my mind.

248
00:15:51,080 --> 00:15:55,520
 I know what it is to go around and around, and I feel that David's got two things that

249
00:15:55,520 --> 00:16:00,600
 can help set you free, two things that can still the war that is taking place in our

250
00:16:00,600 --> 00:16:04,120
 minds as we spiral with anxiety and fear."

251
00:16:04,120 --> 00:16:07,000
 The first of these is found in verse 2.

252
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:13,040
 He says this, "When evil doers came upon me to devour my flesh, my adversaries, and my

253
00:16:13,040 --> 00:16:16,040
 enemies, they stumbled and fell."

254
00:16:16,040 --> 00:16:19,440
 It's really beautiful what David does here.

255
00:16:19,440 --> 00:16:23,800
 If you read it in some of the more modern translations, they don't capture the kind

256
00:16:23,800 --> 00:16:27,720
 of past tense that the Hebrew is written in, but you've got to read it in this way.

257
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:34,400
 When evil doers came upon me in the past to devour my flesh, my adversaries, and my enemies,

258
00:16:34,400 --> 00:16:37,320
 they stumbled and they fell.

259
00:16:37,320 --> 00:16:40,280
 So I want you to see what David is trying to teach his people here.

260
00:16:40,280 --> 00:16:44,480
 He's like, "Here's the first thing you have to realize if you want to win the battle in

261
00:16:44,480 --> 00:16:46,540
 your mind in seasons of waiting.

262
00:16:46,540 --> 00:16:53,980
 It is this, that God has acted in the past, and he says to himself, he says, 'Hang on

263
00:16:53,980 --> 00:16:55,360
 a sec.

264
00:16:55,360 --> 00:16:59,860
 Right now, these new armies, they've encamped around me, and I'm feeling this anxiety and

265
00:16:59,860 --> 00:17:02,300
 fear because I'm thinking the worst thing will happen.'"

266
00:17:02,300 --> 00:17:05,580
 He goes, "But in the past."

267
00:17:05,580 --> 00:17:08,620
 This is not the first time people have warred against me.

268
00:17:08,620 --> 00:17:11,260
 This is not the first time that enemies have encamped around me.

269
00:17:11,260 --> 00:17:14,700
 This is not the first time that there's been rumors of war against me.

270
00:17:14,700 --> 00:17:19,660
 Now I can remember back to just a couple of years ago when it happened before then and

271
00:17:19,660 --> 00:17:21,100
 God came through.

272
00:17:21,100 --> 00:17:26,060
 I can remember back to that battle that I thought was going to take place, and God scattered

273
00:17:26,060 --> 00:17:27,060
 the armies.

274
00:17:27,060 --> 00:17:31,220
 I remember when they started charging at us, they stumbled and they fell.

275
00:17:31,220 --> 00:17:36,500
 When God did it in the past, I need to remember that because what God did before, I believe

276
00:17:36,500 --> 00:17:39,140
 he can do again.

277
00:17:39,140 --> 00:17:44,100
 So what David is trying to stir up with his people is, he's like, "You've got to remember.

278
00:17:44,100 --> 00:17:45,620
 You've got to remember."

279
00:17:45,620 --> 00:17:46,740
 But here's the important thing.

280
00:17:46,740 --> 00:17:53,820
 You see, one of the most destructive things about fear is that it creates forgetfulness.

281
00:17:53,820 --> 00:17:55,300
 Come on, church.

282
00:17:55,300 --> 00:18:01,620
 One of the most destructive things about fear is that it creates in us forgetfulness because

283
00:18:01,620 --> 00:18:06,660
 fear is this immediacy of issues and problems, and we feel overwhelmed, and we want to retreat,

284
00:18:06,660 --> 00:18:08,700
 and we want to hide.

285
00:18:08,700 --> 00:18:12,820
 Anxiety makes us flight away, run away from the reality of the issues.

286
00:18:12,820 --> 00:18:17,100
 Fear can be so overwhelming that it's very easy for our minds to actually forget that

287
00:18:17,100 --> 00:18:21,340
 just last week, God answered a prayer for us.

288
00:18:21,340 --> 00:18:25,940
 And now here we are, spiraling out of control, going, "God never answers my prayer," and

289
00:18:25,940 --> 00:18:32,700
 God's like, "Dude, don't you remember last week when you prayed and I came through?

290
00:18:32,700 --> 00:18:38,500
 Don't you remember two years ago when you faced the same situation at work and I spoke?

291
00:18:38,500 --> 00:18:44,100
 Don't you remember that when you were lonely in that season, I brought alongside that person?

292
00:18:44,100 --> 00:18:45,100
 Don't you remember?"

293
00:18:45,100 --> 00:18:53,260
 And it's like, "No, we don't remember," because fear can so often create forgetfulness.

294
00:18:53,260 --> 00:18:59,220
 Some of you are in a season of waiting right now, and fear and anxiety is absolutely a

295
00:18:59,220 --> 00:19:00,700
 part of that journey for you.

296
00:19:00,700 --> 00:19:06,740
 I want you to understand that one of the greatest tools that you have received is the ability

297
00:19:06,740 --> 00:19:13,860
 to look back to the goodness of God in your past, remember that, and then see that as

298
00:19:13,860 --> 00:19:17,780
 a deposit to His faithfulness for your present and your future.

299
00:19:17,780 --> 00:19:22,300
 It's one of the greatest tools He's placed upon you, is your ability to remember what

300
00:19:22,300 --> 00:19:23,860
 He has done for you before.

301
00:19:23,860 --> 00:19:29,180
 David's like, "Here's how we fight anxiety and the spiraling of our minds, number one.

302
00:19:29,180 --> 00:19:34,420
 I remember the battles when God came through.

303
00:19:34,420 --> 00:19:36,700
 I'm about to face a new battle.

304
00:19:36,700 --> 00:19:37,700
 Guess what?

305
00:19:37,700 --> 00:19:40,780
 He did it before, He can do it again."

306
00:19:40,780 --> 00:19:42,780
 Didn't we all just sing that together?

307
00:19:42,780 --> 00:19:46,420
 It's easy to sing a song, it's different to actually live a life.

308
00:19:46,420 --> 00:19:47,940
 Come on, church.

309
00:19:47,940 --> 00:19:51,660
 It's easy for us to get excited about, "Yeah, yeah, yeah, got that."

310
00:19:51,660 --> 00:19:55,740
 But when the push comes to the shove, when the rubber really hits the road, can we actually

311
00:19:55,740 --> 00:20:01,460
 say these words, "I believe that He can do it again"?

312
00:20:01,460 --> 00:20:06,260
 Not Andrew believes that He can do it again, not my church community believes that He can

313
00:20:06,260 --> 00:20:11,420
 do it again, not even, let me say this and listen to me, that the Scriptures believe

314
00:20:11,420 --> 00:20:12,940
 that He can do it again.

315
00:20:12,940 --> 00:20:15,540
 I believe.

316
00:20:15,540 --> 00:20:17,380
 I stand on the promises.

317
00:20:17,380 --> 00:20:22,500
 I know that He has fought that battle for me before and He will fight it for me again.

318
00:20:22,500 --> 00:20:26,420
 And I don't know when it will happen, I don't know how it's going to happen, and is it hard

319
00:20:26,420 --> 00:20:27,420
 right now?

320
00:20:27,420 --> 00:20:34,620
 Absolutely it is, but I have an active anticipation of change that the God in my past is still

321
00:20:34,620 --> 00:20:40,540
 the God in my present.

322
00:20:40,540 --> 00:20:44,140
 This is a principle throughout Scripture and in the New Testament, this is something really

323
00:20:44,140 --> 00:20:45,380
 important for the early church.

324
00:20:45,380 --> 00:20:50,940
 I want to show you a passage just quickly from Peter writing in 2 Peter chapter 3, writing

325
00:20:50,940 --> 00:20:53,900
 to a church, give you the context.

326
00:20:53,900 --> 00:20:57,860
 He's writing into a church that are waiting for the return of Jesus.

327
00:20:57,860 --> 00:21:02,220
 So Jesus has gone to the cross, He's died, He's paid price for sin, He's raised from

328
00:21:02,220 --> 00:21:07,300
 the dead, He's met with all the disciples and with the church, He's told them and taught

329
00:21:07,300 --> 00:21:09,860
 them and met with them, He's then ascended to heaven.

330
00:21:09,860 --> 00:21:11,860
 Before He ascends He says, "I will return."

331
00:21:11,860 --> 00:21:16,060
 They're expecting the return of Jesus and they're expecting the return of Jesus to happen

332
00:21:16,060 --> 00:21:24,580
 very quickly, and they need it because they're suffering in the first century, in dealing

333
00:21:24,580 --> 00:21:27,040
 with their faith amongst a very hostile environment.

334
00:21:27,040 --> 00:21:31,820
 So the church of Peter are crying out and they're like, "Lord, would you return?"

335
00:21:31,820 --> 00:21:36,260
 And they're feeling more and more anxious that He hasn't come yet, and in 2 Peter 3

336
00:21:36,260 --> 00:21:39,700
 says this, "Dear friends, this is my second letter to you.

337
00:21:39,700 --> 00:21:45,700
 I have written both of them as reminders to stimulate you to wholesome thinking.

338
00:21:45,700 --> 00:21:48,740
 Thumbs up if you need some wholesome thinking."

339
00:21:48,740 --> 00:21:52,180
 Because here's what happens, in seasons of waiting, our thinking...

340
00:21:52,180 --> 00:21:56,940
 Wow, I was going to say something really cheesy then, and I stopped myself from saying something

341
00:21:56,940 --> 00:22:01,620
 really cheesy, it's not in my notes, so thank God, thank you Lord.

342
00:22:01,620 --> 00:22:03,580
 But our thinking gets really bad.

343
00:22:03,580 --> 00:22:06,060
 I could have said, "My thinking is stinking."

344
00:22:06,060 --> 00:22:07,820
 That was it.

345
00:22:07,820 --> 00:22:11,040
 My thinking gets really bad, okay?

346
00:22:11,040 --> 00:22:17,740
 And here He says, "Actually, when we remember, we are stimulated to wholesome thinking."

347
00:22:17,740 --> 00:22:22,960
 He goes, verse 2, "I want you to recall the words spoken in the past by the holy prophets,

348
00:22:22,960 --> 00:22:26,500
 and the command given by our Lord and Savior through the apostles."

349
00:22:26,500 --> 00:22:31,860
 Verse 8, "Do not forget, but do not forget this one thing, dear friends.

